    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-19T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-19T22:00:00-05:00" n="243"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d243">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860C.24/107a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador to the Polish Government in Exile</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Biddle</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">at London</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-19T23:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 19, 1941—11 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2194. From Hopkins.<note n="75" xml:id="d243fn75">Harry L. Hopkins, head of the
                        Lend-Lease program.</note> Poland included under lend-lease.<note n="76"
                        xml:id="d243fn76">President Roosevelt announced on September 4, 1941, that
                        he had authorized the transfer of various defense articles to the Government
                        of Poland under the Lend-Lease Act, and declared that the resistance of
                        Polish forces was “vital to the defense of the United States.” For text of
                        announcement, see Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>,
                        September 6, 1941, p. 181. A master lend-lease agreement was concluded with
                        Poland on July 1, 1942; for text, see Department of State Executive
                        Agreement Series No. 257, or 56 Stat. 1542.</note> We are now trying to get
                    equipment required for training purposes in Canada. Please advise Sikorski and
                    give him my warm regards.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
